    password: "{{ snow_password | default(omit) }}"
    status_code: [200, 201, 202, 204]
  no_log: true
roles/websphere_jvm_restart/README.md
# websphere_jvm_restart (profile-less payload)

## Payload (NO profile name)
The payload lists JVMs directly under each host:

```yaml
jvm_restart:
  ritm_number: RITM1234
  envs:
    dev:
      hosts:
        devhost01: [server1, server2]
        devhost02: [server3, server4]
How it works
Build inventory (localhost):
adds all payload hosts to umbrella group wsjvm_restart_targets
adds env group wsjvm_restart_targets_<env>
sets hostvars: env_name, ritm_number, host_jvms
Execute (parallel per host):
for each JVM name, discovers:
owner (from ps if running, else install root owner)
profile_dir/profile_bin:
from ps if it contains /profiles/<profile>
else from filesystem search under install roots:
.../profiles/<P>/config/cells/*/nodes/*/servers/<jvm>
batches JVMs by discovered profile_bin + owner
per profile batch:
serverStatus pre to classify STARTED vs STOPPED
start stopped JVMs (nodeagent/dmgr/appserver scripts)
restart started JVMs with PID poll + kill -9
serverStatus post wait using expected STARTED lines for:
Application Server
Node Agent
Deployment Manager
record results with started_ok for all 3 types
Aggregate + notify (localhost):
collects jvm_results from hosts
builds failed_hosts list
posts to ServiceNow
Special STARTED lines
AppServer: ADMU0508I: The Application Server "X" is STARTED
nodeagent: ADMU0508I: The Node Agent "nodeagent" is STARTED
dmgr: ADMU0508I: The Deployment Manager "dmgr" is STARTED
Important note

If your environment has multiple dmgr/nodeagent processes, the PS-based discovery for those two is best-effort. The filesystem lookup is the most reliable when they are stopped.

AAP/AWX notes
Inventory may contain only localhost; do NOT set limit=localhost.
Machine credential must allow SSH to targets and sudo to root.
stop/start uses: sudo su - <owner> -c ... (NOPASSWD recommended).

---

## Explanations / Features (quick)
- **Why remove profile from payload works**: we discover profile via ps/config filesystem and then batch by profile.
- **Why `wsjvm_restart_targets` group**: ensures execution does not run on localhost-only inventory host.
- **Why “membership method” for until**: stable across whitespace/wrapping; exposes `missing_started_lines`.
- **Why `sudo su - owner`**: avoids AIX temp-file permission issues while still running WebSphere scripts as owner.

If you want, I can also provide a **single sample JSON** payload (dev/unit/intg/perf/prod) in this new profile-less format, each env having 2 hosts and 2 JVMs.
